{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "Dominion Energy Virginia commercial customer demand charge service class",
    "num_results": 5,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": null,
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "f5838a65-94ce-4fde-9a94-4517ac5677dc",
        "score": 0.5339658,
        "text": "The document page is from the CAISO Business Practice Manual and includes a table listing various customer classes and their associated data. The table shows customer identifiers, class types (e.g., Small_com, Large70_80, Large80_UP), counts, and dates (all set to 08/01/2008). If an Energy Service Provider (ESP) has no customers in a class, a zero value is recorded, and these are counted in the Commercial I class.\n\nThe text explains the DASR (Direct Access Service Request) process, which facilitates the migration of customers between Load Serving Entities (LSEs) and Utility Distribution Companies (UDCs). This process involves data adjustments to accommodate customer classes, and an interactive exchange of billing history occurs when customers switch services. The UDCs Service Delivery Point identifier is used by the ISO for this purpose.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Congestion_Revenue_Rights/page_53.jpg",
          "page_num": 53,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Congestion Revenue Rights",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "73285e11-3f08-4112-9cf3-66d11f7581b8",
        "score": 0.5092186,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to Demand Response (DR) options and requirements for the California Independent System Operator (CAISO). Key points include:\n\n- **Bid Dispatchable Options**: Available in 60-minute, 15-minute, and 5-minute intervals.\n- **Master File**: Stores a Demand Response Type attribute, \"DR_TYPE\" as \"RDRR,\" which is view-only and based on valid registration.\n- **Load Curtailment**: For resources selecting the Discrete Real-Time Dispatch Option, the maximum load curtailment is capped at 100 MW. There is no cap for those selecting the Marginal Real-Time Dispatch Option.\n\nExceptions to the 100 MW cap can be requested if valid reasons exist. The Demand Response Provider must submit a request via a CIDI ticket with the subject \"Demand Response Attestation,\" including an attestation as per Appendix H of the Business Process Manual. The attestation must confirm that the resource is at a single site, cannot be split into multiple loads, and cannot operate under the Marginal Real-Time Dispatch Option.\n\nCAISO will review the attestation to ensure no significant reliability issues arise. Approval takes about 10 business days. If a resource approved for over 100 MW increases by 50 MW or more, a new attestation is required.\n\nFor any changes to the resource\u2019s Pmax value, the Scheduling Coordinator must update the Generator Resource Data Template (GRDT).\n\nThe document also mentions requirements for setting up the Masterfile.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Demand_Response/page_65.jpg",
          "page_num": 65,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Demand Response",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c50f7d7e-6c42-4dcd-bca6-473b8b65b714",
        "score": 0.5064153,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2014 State of the Market Report for PJM\" and focuses on demand response (DR) in the PJM market. It includes several tables and a summary of DR charges and occurrences in 2013 and 2014.\n\n1. **Table 6-12**: This table shows the number of hours with prices higher than non-bypassable transmission (NBT) and DR occurrences for 2013 and 2014. It provides monthly data, indicating the percentage change in hours with higher prices and DR occurrences.\n\n2. **Summary**: The text discusses the impact of FERC Order No. 745, which requires DR in PJM to be paid based on real-time loads and exports. It highlights the increase in DR charges in 2014, with a significant rise in both day-ahead and real-time DR charges. The total economic DR charges in 2014 were 43.4% of the total, with AEP, Dominion, and ComEd having the highest charges.\n\n3. **Table 6-13**: This table details the zonal DR charges for each month in 2014 across various zones, showing the monthly charges in dollars.\n\n4. **Table 6-14**: It presents the monthly day-ahead and real-time DR charges for 2013 and 2014, showing the percentage change. The day-ahead DR charges increased by 76%, and real-time DR charges increased by 127% from 2013 to 2014. The load charge for DR increased from $0.02/MWh to $0.04/MWh, a 79% increase.\n\nOverall, the document highlights significant increases in DR charges and occurrences, reflecting changes in market dynamics and regulatory impacts.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/PJM/report/2014/page_261.jpg",
          "page_num": 261,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for PJM",
          "year": "2014",
          "market": "PJM",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "368cb2e8-3f3f-4157-93bf-b803c5df1a68",
        "score": 0.50286937,
        "text": "The document is a section from the California Independent System Operator Corporation's Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff. It outlines procedures and requirements related to Demand Response Services.\n\n1. **Meter Data Handling**: \n   - If Meter Data is below 0 MWh, it is considered 0 MWh for curtailment Resource ID.\n   - Energy exceeding onsite demand is excluded from Meter Data.\n\n2. **Scheduling Coordinator Responsibilities**:\n   - Calculate hourly average of collected Meter Data to determine baseline energy amounts for each Resource ID.\n\n3. **Demand Response Provider Options**:\n   - May include Demand Response Energy Measurements for onsite Load.\n   - Separate Customer Load Baseline is calculated if Demand Response Provider elects to include these measurements.\n\n4. **Baseline Calculation Methods**:\n   - Residential onsite Load: Ten-in-ten, five-in-ten, or weather matching methodology.\n   - Non-residential onsite Load: Ten-in-ten or weather matching methodology.\n\n5. **Characteristics of PDRs and RDRRs**:\n   - **Availability**: Proxy Demand Resource (PDR) and Reliability Demand Response Resource (RDRR) become available after the Demand Response Provider Agreement is executed.\n   - **Size Limits**: Minimum load curtailment for a PDR is 0.1 MW, with no upper limit.\n\nThe document is dated November 1, 2024, and is part of Section 4.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Fifth_Replacement_FERC_Electric_Tariff/page_84.jpg",
          "page_num": 84,
          "title": "Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "32553ff8-7ad3-4ec1-81a6-2bf253439350",
        "score": 0.4933151,
        "text": "The document discusses the California Independent System Operator's (CAISO) recognition of a fourth demand response resource type, the Distributed Curtailment Resource (DCR), as part of a Distributed Energy Resource Aggregation (DERA). This resource type uses the same performance measurement processes as other products.\n\n1. **Proxy Demand Resource (PDR):** Developed to increase demand response participation in CAISO's wholesale Energy and Ancillary Services markets, facilitating existing retail demand response integration.\n\n2. **Reliability Demand Response Resource (RDRR):** Aimed at increasing demand response by integrating emergency-triggered retail programs. RDRRs can bid in the day-ahead market but are dispatched for reliability in real-time. They cannot offer Ancillary Services or submit RUC availability bids without local regulatory approval.\n\n3. **Proxy Demand Resource - Load Shift Resource (PDR-LSR):** Recognizes demand's ability to consume during oversupply, allowing it to shift and shape load based on market signals.\n\n4. **Distributed Curtailment Resource (DCR):** Defined as a resource type for DERA, compliant with FERC order 2222. DERAs can include DCRs to support both curtailment and energy injection. The Demand Curtailment is calculated using the Demand Response Energy Measurement (DREM).\n\nThe document also notes that DCRs will be metered as supply, requiring meter data and baseline monitoring data submissions according to existing timelines.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Demand_Response/page_12.jpg",
          "page_num": 12,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Demand Response",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

